defaultTom Riordandefault: The argument, which we have had echoed in the points that have been made so far, is that local growth is national growth.  If we can find ways to empower the local actors and partnerships through the powers that they have, their wider freedoms and flexibilities, and to back that up with meaningful devolution in fiscal terms, then you are enabling those areas better to engage with and to stimulate growth in their local areas.  The addition of greater stimulation of growth in all those local areas adds up to greater national growth. 
